  "prompt": "Do satellites emit color when viewed in the night sky?",
  "response": "Satellites themselves do not emit light or color. When viewed from the Earth, they typically appear as small, moving points of light in the night sky. This is because they reflect sunlight rather than emitting their own light. The color you might see can be influenced by several factors, such as the satellite's altitude, its material, and the angle of sunlight reflecting off its surface. Most often, they appear white or slightly yellowish, similar to stars. Some specific satellites, like the International Space Station (ISS), can appear brighter due to their larger size and reflective surfaces.",
